  "Question": "<p>We know that for a group element <span class=\"math-container\" id=\"q_495\"><?xml version=\"1.0\" encoding=\"UTF-8\"?> <math alttext=\"g\\in G\" display=\"block\" xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"> <mrow> <mi>g</mi> <mo>\u2208</mo> <mi>G</mi> </mrow> </math></span>, <span class=\"math-container\" id=\"q_496\"><?xml version=\"1.0\" encoding=\"UTF-8\"?> <math alttext=\"gh=1\" display=\"block\" xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"> <mrow> <mrow> <mi>g</mi> <mo>\u2062</mo> <mi>h</mi> </mrow> <mo>=</mo> <mn>1</mn> </mrow> </math></span> does not necessarily mean that <span class=\"math-container\" id=\"q_497\"><?xml version=\"1.0\" encoding=\"UTF-8\"?> <math alttext=\"hg=1\" display=\"block\" xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"> <mrow> <mrow> <mi>h</mi> <mo>\u2062</mo> <mi>g</mi> </mrow> <mo>=</mo> <mn>1</mn> </mrow> </math></span>. In the case for matrices (linear maps between vector spaces), it is also true that <span class=\"math-container\" id=\"q_498\"><?xml version=\"1.0\" encoding=\"UTF-8\"?> <math alttext=\"AB=1\\nRightarrow BA=1\" display=\"block\" xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"> <mrow> <mrow> <mi>A</mi> <mo>\u2062</mo> <mi>B</mi> </mrow> <mo>=</mo> <mrow> <mn>1</mn> <mo>\u2062</mo> <merror class=\"ltx_ERROR undefined undefined\"> <mtext>\\nRightarrow</mtext> </merror> <mo>\u2062</mo> <mi>B</mi> <mo>\u2062</mo> <mi>A</mi> </mrow> <mo>=</mo> <mn>1</mn> </mrow> </math></span>. This happens when the <span class=\"math-container\" id=\"q_499\"><?xml version=\"1.0\" encoding=\"UTF-8\"?> <math alttext=\"A\" display=\"block\" xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"> <mi>A</mi> </math></span> and <span class=\"math-container\" id=\"q_500\"><?xml version=\"1.0\" encoding=\"UTF-8\"?> <math alttext=\"B\" display=\"block\" xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"> <mi>B</mi> </math></span> are not square matrices (in which case they do not even form a group under multiplication).</p> <p>However if we restrict the square matrices, <span class=\"math-container\" id=\"q_501\"><?xml version=\"1.0\" encoding=\"UTF-8\"?> <math alttext=\"AB=1\\Rightarrow BA=1\" display=\"block\" xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"> <mrow> <mrow> <mi>A</mi> <mo>\u2062</mo> <mi>B</mi> </mrow> <mo>=</mo> <mn>1</mn> <mo>\u21d2</mo> <mrow> <mi>B</mi> <mo>\u2062</mo> <mi>A</mi> </mrow> <mo>=</mo> <mn>1</mn> </mrow> </math></span>. What is simple proof of this that avoids chasing the entries, and makes use simply the vector space structure of linear transformations?</p> <p>(In fact if we could prove this, I think this might imply that for a group to have one-sided(but not two-sided) inverses, it has to be infinite, since every finite group admits a finite dimensional representation.</p>",
  "Title": "Show that one-sided inverse of a square matrix is a true inverse",
  "Tags": "linear-algebra,group-theory"
